Here's the complete migration from ASP.NET Framework WebForms to ASP.NET Core 8 MVC:

## Migrated Code

```csharp
// ASP.NET Core 8 — ReportController.cs
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // No Response.Clear/Write/End — just return a result object.
        // The framework handles headers and body writing.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Response.Redirect(url, true) used Thread.Abort to stop execution.
            // In Core, just return a RedirectResult — nothing after this runs.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No ThreadAbortException catch — it doesn't exist in modern .NET.
        // OperationCanceledException is the cooperative equivalent if needed.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "Request processing failed");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Changes & Pitfalls

| Old Pattern | New Pattern | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | **Remove entirely** — return from the action | Calls `Thread.Abort` internally; throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` | The `true` (endResponse) param triggered `Thread.Abort`; returning an `IActionResult` naturally ends execution |
| `Response.Write(data)` + headers | `return File(bytes, contentType, filename)` | Core's action results handle the full response lifecycle |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Remove the catch block** | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown in modern .NET; the swallow pattern is unnecessary |
| `Response.Clear()` / `AddHeader()` | Handled by `FileResult` | Action results set headers correctly; no manual clearing needed |

## Critical Pitfalls

1. **`Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`**: Any surviving `Thread.Abort()` call will throw at runtime, not compile-time. Search your entire codebase for `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, and `Thread.ResetAbort`.

2. **Code after redirect still runs**: In WebForms, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` aborted the thread so nothing below it executed. In Core, `Redirect()` returns an object — **code after it keeps running** unless you `return` it. Always `return Redirect(...)`.

3. **Null-safety on `User.Identity`**: In Core, `User.Identity` can be null if no auth middleware runs. Use `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`.

4. **No `catch (OperationCanceledException)` needed here**: The old `ThreadAbortException` catch was only there because `Response.Redirect` threw it. Since `return Redirect()` doesn't throw, no equivalent catch is needed. Only catch `OperationCanceledException` if you're doing long-running work with `HttpContext.RequestAborted`.

5. **WebForms event handlers → action methods**: `btnExport_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)` becomes `[HttpPost] public IActionResult Export()`. Route via `<form asp-action="Export">` or AJAX, not server-side button events.
